gomodel:SYNGO_3912  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Rat cultured hippocampal neurons transfected at DIV19 with FLAG-RhebQ64V (Inactive RHEB) completely abolished spine synapse formation in WT neurons.\n\n18/01/2021 Dnyanada : Tuberous sclerosis complex (TSC) is a systemic genetic disease that demonstrates impaired spine formation (Figure 1). The paper investigates the role of RHEB, a GTPase located downstream of the TSC 1/2 complex in the impaired spine formation phenotype. Expression of active Rheb (FLAG-RhebQ64V ) abolishes dendritic spine formation in WT neurons, whereas inactive Rheb (FLAG-RhebD60I) restores spine synapse formation in Tsc2+/- neurons. Furthermore, inactivation of Rheb with farnesyltransferase inhibitors recoveres spine synapse morphogenesis in Tsc2+/- neurons.\nBased on these observations on spine formation, the term \"regulation of postsynapse organization\" was selected.. Experimental description: Rat cultured hippocampal neurons\n\n24/09/2018 Pim\n- \"In this study, we used spontaneous Tsc2-mutated Eker rats as animal models of TSC11. We first compared dendritic spine morphology of cultured hippocampal neurons of wild type (WT) and heterozygous Eker (Tsc2+/-) rats.\"\n- Species of over-expressed RHEB is not stated in the publication. The authors were contacted for additional information (dd 24/9/2018, yamagata-kn@igakuken.or.jp). Answer:" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2094-7491" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4419-210X" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9848-0262" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1190-4481" ;
        dc:date           "2021-01-18" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3912" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

